            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this auto loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This auto loan calculator uses the standard amortizing loan
                formula to estimate your monthly payment and total interest. It
                lets you include real‑world items like taxes, fees, trade‑ins,
                rebates, and extra payments so you can see the full picture
                before you sign.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Payment calculation formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Monthly payment formula</p>
                <p>For a fixed‑rate auto loan, the monthly payment \(M\) is:</p>
                <p>\[ M = P \times \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(P\) = amount financed (loan principal)</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = monthly interest rate (APR ÷ 12)</li>
                  <li>\(n\) = total number of payments (months)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Amount financed vs. vehicle price</h3>
              <p>
                The amount you actually borrow is usually different from the
                sticker price. The calculator computes:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Amount financed} = \text{Price} + \text{Taxes &amp;
                  fees} - \text{Down payment} - \text{Trade‑in} - \text{Rebates}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If this value is negative (for example, very large down
                payment), the loan amount is treated as zero.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Extra payments and interest savings</h3>
              <p>
                When you add an extra monthly payment, the calculator simulates
                the amortization month by month. Each month:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Interest = current balance × monthly rate</li>
                <li>Principal = payment − interest</li>
                <li>New balance = old balance − principal</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Extra payments increase the principal portion, which reduces the
                balance faster, shortens the payoff time, and cuts total
                interest. The tool shows your new payoff time and estimated
                interest savings.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Affordability: solving for price from a budget</h3>
              <p>
                In the Affordability tab, the calculator works backwards. Given
                a target monthly payment \(M\), APR, and term \(n\), it solves
                for the maximum loan amount \(P\):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ P = M \times \frac{(1+r)^n - 1}{r(1+r)^n} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Then it adds your down payment, trade‑in, and subtracts
                estimated taxes and fees to estimate the maximum vehicle price.
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for choosing the right auto loan</h2>
              <h3>Watch the total cost, not just the payment</h3>
              <p>
                Dealers can stretch your term to make any car “fit” your monthly
                budget, but that often means paying thousands more in interest.
                Compare:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monthly payment</strong> – can you comfortably afford
                  it every month?
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total interest</strong> – how much extra are you
                  paying for financing?
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Loan term</strong> – longer than 72 months is usually
                  a red flag.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>New vs. used, and interest rates</h3>
              <p>
                New cars and shorter terms usually qualify for lower APRs. Used
                cars, long terms, and weaker credit scores tend to have higher
                rates. Use the APR slider to see how rate changes affect your
                payment and total cost.
              </p>

              <h3>Down payment and trade‑in strategy</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Aim for at least 10–20% down on new cars and more on used
                  cars.
                </li>
                <li>
                  A larger down payment reduces your loan amount and interest,
                  and helps avoid being upside‑down.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Know your trade‑in value (from sites like KBB or Edmunds)
                  before negotiating.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Avoid common auto loan pitfalls</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Rolling negative equity from an old loan into a new one.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Focusing only on the monthly payment instead of total cost.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Accepting add‑ons (extended warranties, GAP, extras) without
                  understanding their cost.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Not shopping around: always compare offers from banks, credit
                  unions, and online lenders.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>What credit score do I need for a good auto loan rate?</h3>
              <p>
                Lenders typically reserve their best rates for borrowers with
                excellent credit (often 750+ FICO), but many will finance buyers
                with scores in the 600s or even lower at higher rates. Improving
                your score before buying can save substantial interest.
              </p>

              <h3>Is 0% financing always the best deal?</h3>
              <p>
                Not always. Sometimes you must choose between 0% financing and a
                large cash rebate. Use this calculator to compare:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Scenario A: higher price with 0% APR.</li>
                <li>Scenario B: lower price (rebate) with a standard APR.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The option with the lower total cost (price + interest) is the
                better financial deal.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I refinance my existing auto loan?</h3>
              <p>
                Refinancing can make sense if interest rates have dropped, your
                credit has improved, or you want a shorter term. Enter your
                remaining balance as the “amount financed” and compare your
                current payment and total interest with a new rate and term.
              </p>
